	</form></div><span class="pb doctop" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-10-02-pb-0294">294<a style="padding-left: 5px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-10/ADMS-06-10-02-pb-0294.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a></span><div id="PJA10d196" class="doc letter">

    <h1>From Benjamin Franklin</h1>
    
    <div class="docbody">
     <div class="opener">
      <table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Passy 20 Oct. 1780</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
     </div>
     <p>Understanding that in Case of Mr. Laurenss Absence, you are charged with the Affair of procuring a Loan in Holland, I think it Right to acquaint you, that by a Letter from Mr. Jay of the 12th. Instant, from Madrid, we are informed that the King of Spain has been so good as to offer his Guarrantee for the Payment of the Interest and Principal of a Loan of Money for the Use of the United States.<a class="ptr" href="#PJA10d196n1" id="PJA10d196n1-ptr">1</a> Mr. Grand thinks that no considerable Use can be made here of that Guarrantee, on Account of the considerable Loan Mr. Necker is about to make;<a class="ptr" href="#PJA10d196n2" id="PJA10d196n2-ptr">2</a> but that possibly it may have weight in Holland. Orders will be sent to the Spanish Ambassador here, by the next Post respecting this Matter.</p>
     <p>I regret much the taking of Mr. Laurens. His Son, I understand sailed a Fortnight after him, for France; but he has not yet arrived.<a class="ptr" href="#PJA10d196n3" id="PJA10d196n3-ptr">3</a></p>
     <p>The Ariel has been at Sea, but meeting with a terrible Storm which carried away all her Masts, has returnd into Port to refit.<a class="ptr" href="#PJA10d196n4" id="PJA10d196n4-ptr">4</a></p>
     <p>I have the honour to be with great Respect, Sir, Your Excellencys most obedient &amp; most humble Sert.</p>
     <div class="closer">
      <p class="signed">B Franklin</p>
     </div>
     <div class="postscript">
      <p>P.S. By a former Letter from Mr. Jay I find the Sum to be one hundred and fifty thousand Dollars, for which the King of Spain would be answerable payable in the Space of 3 Years.</p>
     </div>
    </div>
    <div class="docback">
     <div class="note-source" id="PJA10d196sn1">
      
   <p>
       <span class="docSource"><span class="dType"><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ recipients copy (A recipients copy is assumed to be in the hand of the signer unless it is otherwise described.) ]">RC</abbr></span> (<span class="ref-terms">Adams Papers</span>); endorsed: His Excellency Dr Franklin recd and ansd 24. Octr. 1780 Warranty of Spain for a Loan.</span>
      </p>

     </div>
     <div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA10d196n1-ptr" id="PJA10d196n1">1</a>
      
   <p>Neither this letter from John Jay to Franklin nor that mentioned in the postscript has been found, but see Jays letter of 16 Sept. to the president of Congress in which he conveyed the same information (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Francis Wharton, ed., &lt;i&gt;The Revolutionary Diplomatic Correspondence of the United States&lt;/i&gt;, Washington, 1889; 6 vols. ]">Wharton, ed., <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Dipl. Corr. Amer. Rev.</span></span>, 4:59).</p>

     </div>
     <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA10d196n2-ptr" id="PJA10d196n2">2</a>
      
   <p>Raised in November, the loan totalled 36,000,000 (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Jonathan R. Dull, &lt;i&gt;The French Navy and American Independence: A Study of Arms and Diplomacy, 17741787&lt;/i&gt;, Princeton, 1975. ]">Dull, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">French Navy and Amer. Independence</span></span>, p. 199).</p>

     </div>
     <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA10d196n3-ptr" id="PJA10d196n3">3</a>
      
   <p>John Laurens, appointed in December to raise a loan in France, did not sail from Boston until Feb. 1781 and reached Paris in mid-March (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington C. Ford and others, eds., &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 17741789&lt;/i&gt;, Washington, 19041937; 34 vols. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span></span>, 18:1141; <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ David Duncan Wallace, &lt;i&gt;Life of Henry Laurens&lt;/i&gt;, New York, 1915. ]">Wallace, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Life of Henry Laurens</span></span>, p. 480).</p>

     </div>
     <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA10d196n4-ptr" id="PJA10d196n4">4</a>
      
   <p>For an account of John Paul Jones ordeal in saving the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Ariel</span>, see <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Samuel Eliot Morison, &lt;i&gt;John Paul Jones, a Sailors Biography&lt;/i&gt;, Boston and Toronto, 1959. ]">Morison, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">John Paul Jones</span></span>, p. 301306.</p>

     </div>
    </div>
